<!-- =================== R11 NEGATIVE FINDINGS =================== -->
<h3>R11. Provenance for <i>negative</i> findings</h3>
<p><b>What.</b> Today <code>claim_provenance</code> records what was <i>produced</i>. There's no record of what was <i>looked for and not found.</i> For a truth platform, negative space is information. When the multi-LLM verifier rejects a claim, when the hallucination check fires, when an indicator was unavailable for a country, when no contradicting source was found &mdash; each should be a row of its own type.</p>

<h4>Impact graph</h4>
<table class=impact>
<tr class=r-blast-med><td><b>Schema</b></td><td>Migration <code>030_negative_provenance.sql</code> &mdash; widen <code>claim_provenance.event_type</code> enum to include <code>claim_rejected</code>, <code>hallucination_flagged</code>, <code>indicator_missing</code>, <code>no_contradiction_found</code>, <code>numeric_grounding_failed</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>Callers</td><td><code>multi_llm_verifier.py</code> (write a row when corroboration fails), <code>hallucination_detector.py</code> (when score &gt; threshold), <code>sustainability_score.py</code> (when an indicator is missing for a country), <code>deep_search_service.py</code> (when synthesis abstains)</td></tr>
<tr><td>API</td><td>New filter on <code>/api/methodology/audit-trail/*</code>: <code>?include_negative=true</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>Frontend</td><td><code>MethodologyDrawer</code> shows a "What we looked for and didn't find" section when negative rows exist</td></tr>
</table>

<h4>Effects</h4>
<ul>
  <li>Transparency: complete provenance graph &mdash; the audit trail now answers "is this absence of evidence informative?"</li>
  <li>Calibration input: negative events become training signal for the calibration labels (rejected claims that were correct rejections improve the calibrated reliability score).</li>
</ul>

<h4>Risk &amp; rollback</h4>
<p>Risk: <b>low</b>. Pure schema widening + writes. Reads degrade gracefully if the new column types are absent.</p>

<!-- =================== R12 INDICATOR CONFIDENCE =================== -->
<h3>R12. Indicator confidence &mdash; per-source &sigma;</h3>
<p><b>What.</b> Each <code>country_indicators</code> row knows <i>when</i> it was ingested but not how confident the platform is in the upstream number itself. OWID per-capita emissions for Eritrea 2023 is plausibly &plusmn;30%; for Germany 2023 plausibly &plusmn;2%. The sustainability composite treats both as point estimates. Add an <code>uncertainty_sigma</code> column; propagate through the composite using standard error propagation.</p>

<h4>Impact graph</h4>
<table class=impact>
<tr class=r-blast-med><td><b>Schema</b></td><td>Migration <code>031_indicator_uncertainty.sql</code> &mdash; <code>country_indicators.uncertainty_sigma NUMERIC</code>, <code>country_indicators.distribution_shape VARCHAR</code> (default normal)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Adapters</td><td>Each of the six adapters now writes the upstream's stated uncertainty (Climate TRACE publishes a method-uncertainty per sector; OWID publishes 1&ndash;5 quality tiers; CAT has band-half-width; ND-GAIN provides confidence intervals)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Composite</td><td><code>sustainability_score.py</code> &mdash; propagate uncertainty via <code>sigma_composite&sup2; = &sum;w&sub;i&sup2; * sigma&sub;i&sup2;</code>; this <i>replaces</i> the heuristic <code>confidence_band</code> with a defensible computed value</td></tr>
<tr><td>API</td><td>Each indicator value now ships with <code>{value, uncertainty, distribution}</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>UI</td><td>Decomposed gauge (R5) renders error bars on each bar &mdash; ties R5 and R12 together</td></tr>
</table>

<h4>Effects</h4>
<ul>
  <li>Sustainability axis lift: 3.3 &rarr; 4.3.</li>
  <li>Equity correction: low-emitter countries with high-uncertainty data are no longer misleadingly shown as "scoring 30/100" with a tight band.</li>
  <li>Composite grade: <b>+0.05 to +0.10</b>.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Risk &amp; rollback</h4>
<p>Risk: <b>medium</b>. Re-grades every sustainability score in production. Rollback: leave the column nullable; the composite falls back to the v2 fixed bands when <code>uncertainty_sigma IS NULL</code>.</p>

<!-- =================== R13 LEARNED DRIFT THRESHOLDS =================== -->
<h3>R13. Learned drift thresholds</h3>
<p><b>What.</b> KL drift thresholds (0.10 / 0.25 / 0.50 nats) are hard-coded in <code>drift_detection.py:134</code>. Collect 60 days of post-launch baseline data, fit a Gaussian to each drift signal's null distribution, set thresholds at 2&sigma; / 3&sigma; / 4&sigma;. Publish the learned thresholds with their fit windows on <code>/methodology</code>.</p>

<h4>Impact graph</h4>
<table class=impact>
<tr class=r-blast-low><td><b>Primary edit</b></td><td><code>drift_detection.py</code> &mdash; new <code>fit_thresholds(signal, window_days)</code> + persist into a new table <code>drift_threshold_fits</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>Celery</td><td>New task <code>tasks/drift_threshold_refit.py</code> &mdash; weekly</td></tr>
<tr><td>API</td><td><code>/api/methodology/drift-thresholds</code> &mdash; surface the current fits + windows</td></tr>
</table>

<h4>Effects</h4>
<ul>
  <li>Drift axis lift: 4.0 &rarr; 4.7. Avoids the failure mode where a real drift event looks like baseline noise during a too-short baseline window.</li>
  <li>Publishable as metrology evidence &mdash; the strongest data-quality signal a platform can put on its methodology page.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Risk &amp; rollback</h4>
<p>Risk: <b>low</b>. Replaces three constants with a fit. Constants remain as fallback.</p>

<!-- =================== R14 CROSS-LANG HALLUCINATION =================== -->
<h3>R14. Cross-language hallucination &mdash; per-language embeddings + claim clustering</h3>
<p><b>What.</b> The Strategic-analysis report's <i>original-research moat</i>. The hardest problem in climate misinformation in 2026 is multilingual narrative laundering &mdash; a denialist claim debunked in English keeps spreading in Portuguese, Polish, Indonesian. Three sub-projects:</p>
<ul>
  <li><b>Per-language embeddings:</b> replace OpenAI ada-002 (which blunts intra-language signal) with <code>bge-m3</code> or <code>multilingual-e5-large</code>. Re-embed historical articles.</li>
  <li><b>Cross-language claim clustering:</b> a hash-key mapping the <i>same proposition</i> across languages, built from translated claim normalisation plus embedding-based clustering.</li>
  <li><b>Narrative-tracking dashboard:</b> shows a debunked claim's lifecycle across languages.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Impact graph</h4>
<table class=impact>
<tr class=r-blast-high><td><b>Embedding model swap</b></td><td><code>src/backend/app/domains/content/embedding_service.py</code> &mdash; provider-agnostic interface; new HNSW index for the new dimensionality; migration <code>032_multilingual_embeddings.sql</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>New domain</td><td><code>src/backend/app/domains/intelligence/narrative_clustering.py</code> &mdash; claim-cluster hash + cluster-membership table</td></tr>
<tr><td>Schema</td><td>Migration <code>033_narrative_clusters.sql</code> &mdash; <code>narrative_clusters(cluster_id, canonical_text, language_count, member_count, first_seen_at)</code> + <code>claim_cluster_membership(claim_id, cluster_id, language_code, similarity)</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>API</td><td>New endpoints <code>/api/narratives</code>, <code>/api/narratives/{cluster_id}</code> (lifecycle), <code>/api/narratives/{cluster_id}/timeline</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>Frontend</td><td>New route <code>/narratives</code> &mdash; explorer of cross-language narrative clusters</td></tr>
<tr><td>Backfill</td><td>One-off Celery job to re-embed historical articles (~5 hours on the local corpus); cluster build (~1 hour)</td></tr>
</table>

<div class=dag>
gitnexus query:
  graph emit --from narrative_clustering.py --include embeddings,migrations,routes
expected fan-out: ~8 new modules, 2 migrations, 3 routes, 1 frontend route, 6 tests
risk class: HIGH-BUILD (most ambitious item; original research)
</div>

<h4>Effects</h4>
<ul>
  <li>Category position: this is the moat. No other platform has it.</li>
  <li>Multilingual integrity axis: 3.0 &rarr; 4.7.</li>
  <li>Mission fit: directly delivers "anyone, anywhere, in any language" with a structural capability no competitor will match in &lt;12 months.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Risk &amp; rollback</h4>
<p>Risk: <b>high</b>. Embedding model swap re-indexes the corpus; the cluster identity stays language-agnostic which is structurally new. Rollback: keep both embedding indexes for one quarter; route <code>/narratives</code> hidden behind a flag.</p>

<!-- =================== R15 MICROCONTENT =================== -->
<h3>R15. Embed widget + QR fact-check cards</h3>
<p><b>What.</b> The light version of the deferred Phase-9 video pipeline. Auto-generate one-claim fact-check cards (1080&times;1080 + 1080&times;1920) from any URL-analysis result, with verdict + two-source citation + methodology link + QR code back to the full audit trail. Plus an <code>&lt;iframe&gt;</code> embed widget for newsrooms; plus a Slack/Teams app.</p>

<h4>Impact graph</h4>
<table class=impact>
<tr class=r-blast-low><td><b>New module</b></td><td><code>api/factcard_routes.py</code> &mdash; reuse <code>og_image_routes.py</code>'s Pillow / Resvg pattern; add square + vertical variants + QR code</td></tr>
<tr><td>Reuse</td><td><code>api/og_image_routes.py</code> (already generates social cards); <code>infographic_generator.py</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>Embed widget</td><td><code>src/frontend/src/app/embed/[analysis_id]/page.tsx</code> &mdash; minimal iframe-friendly layout; explicit <code>&lt;iframe&gt;</code> sandbox advice in the share modal</td></tr>
<tr><td>QR</td><td><code>qrcode</code> library; URL pattern <code>https://climatefacts.ai/a/{short_id}?utm=fact-card</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>Slack/Teams app</td><td>New service <code>src/backend/services/slack_integration_service/</code> &mdash; uses existing <code>/api/url-analysis</code></td></tr>
</table>

<h4>Effects</h4>
<ul>
  <li>Distribution: each shared card is a viral surface that links back to the platform.</li>
  <li>80% of the impact of the video pipeline at 20% of the engineering and zero of the social-platform-API risk.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Risk &amp; rollback</h4>
<p>Risk: <b>low</b>. Additive routes; nothing else changes.</p>

<!-- =================== R16 FAIR + IMMUTABLE LEDGER =================== -->
<h3>R16. FAIR metadata + immutable audit ledger</h3>
<p><b>What.</b> The FAIR/dMRV report's Tier-1 anchor. Two sub-components:</p>
<ul>
  <li><b>FAIR metadata layer:</b> persistent identifier per dataset (DOI-style), rich metadata aligned to F1&ndash;F4 / A1 / I1&ndash;I3 / R1, registered with <code>data.europa.eu</code> / <code>re3data.org</code>. A FAIR-compliance score published per dataset.</li>
  <li><b>Immutable ledger:</b> anchor critical datasets &mdash; emissions inventories, carbon credits, NDC reports &mdash; to a Hyperledger Fabric consortium chain (sovereignty-friendly; no public chain for compliance reasons). Each anchoring event records data hash + timestamp + submitting entity + methodology applied. Users can verify any displayed value has not been altered post-publication.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Impact graph</h4>
<table class=impact>
<tr class=r-blast-high><td><b>FAIR module</b></td><td>New <code>src/backend/app/domains/trust/fair_metadata.py</code> + per-dataset YAML manifests under <code>infrastructure/fair/datasets/</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>Ledger module</td><td>New <code>src/backend/services/ledger_service/</code> &mdash; Hyperledger Fabric SDK + Merkle-tree anchoring + verification CLI</td></tr>
<tr><td>Schema</td><td>Migration <code>034_ledger_anchors.sql</code> &mdash; <code>ledger_anchors(anchor_id, dataset_id, data_hash_sha256, merkle_root, fabric_txid, anchored_at, methodology_version)</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>API</td><td><code>/api/methodology/fair</code> (compliance scores), <code>/api/methodology/anchor/{id}</code> (proof retrieval), <code>/api/methodology/verify?dataset_id=&hellip;</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>Frontend</td><td>Verification badge tier 3 (&#10004;&#10004;&#10004; cryptographically anchored) on every relevant surface</td></tr>
<tr><td>Ops</td><td>Hyperledger network &mdash; either consortium with partners (preferred) or single-org local for MVP; CAD Trust integration as fallback if Article-6.2 ITMOs become relevant</td></tr>
</table>

<div class=dag>
gitnexus query:
  graph emit --from ledger_service/ --include all
expected fan-out: ~12 new modules, 2 migrations, 4 routes, 1 service folder, 8 tests, 1 ops doc
risk class: HIGH-BUILD + HIGH-OPS (most operationally complex item; needs partner co-signature)
</div>

<h4>Effects</h4>
<ul>
  <li>Category position: this <i>defines</i> the "universal trust layer" the FAIR/dMRV report describes. Sets the platform up to be the <b>infrastructure</b> on which others build, not a product that competes with them.</li>
  <li>Regulatory fit: directly aligned with UNFCCC Climate Data Hub (Feb 2026), CAD Trust (carbon-credit anti-double-counting), Gold Standard dMRV pilot (running to October 2026).</li>
  <li>Commercial: the white-label / Enterprise SKU now has a defensible <i>technical</i> moat, not just a brand one.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Risk &amp; rollback</h4>
<p>Risk: <b>high</b>. Most operationally complex item in the backlog. <b>Sequence late</b> &mdash; only after R10 (corporate claims) creates a population of high-stakes claims worth anchoring. Rollback: ledger writes are write-through; reads can fall back to DB-only audit trail with no functional loss.</p>

<!-- ============================== 5. SEQUENCED 12-WEEK PLAN ============================== -->
<h2>5. Sequenced 12-week plan</h2>

<table>
<tr><th>Week</th><th>Recommendations</th><th>Rationale</th></tr>
<tr><td>1</td><td>R3 (audit-trail join) + R8 (publish self-audit on /methodology) + R5 (decomposed gauge wired in &mdash; the component already exists)</td><td>Three low-risk, high-trust-signal moves that take advantage of the post-launch composite (~4.0/5) climbing to 4.2 with two days of focused front-end work.</td></tr>
<tr><td>2</td><td>R4 (AI Act labelling layer) + R1 (source-tier DB, behind flag)</td><td>R4 cashes the EU AI Act August window; R1 closes the audit's largest single gap. Both shippable in parallel.</td></tr>
<tr><td>3&ndash;4</td><td>R2 (agentic chat actions)</td><td>Biggest UX uplift; nine action types ship together; ground in <code>chat_actions_log</code> for telemetry.</td></tr>
<tr><td>5</td><td>R9 (adversarial auditor-persona prompts) + R11 (negative-finding provenance)</td><td>Strengthens the multi-LLM verifier; opens the audit trail's negative space &mdash; both prerequisites for R10.</td></tr>
<tr><td>6&ndash;8</td><td>R10 (corporate-claim MVP &mdash; CDP + SBTi + NZT + <code>/companies/[ticker]</code>)</td><td>The single highest-leverage strategic bet. Three weeks because three adapters + schema + frontend page + scheduler triggers. <b>Ships before September 2026 ECGT enforcement.</b></td></tr>
<tr><td>9</td><td>R7 (per-country claim ledger) + R6 (reproduce button) + R15 (embed widget + QR fact-cards)</td><td>Three distribution / journalistic-utility moves that complement the corporate-claim MVP: ledger view for countries, reproduce button for any past analysis, shareable cards for every verdict.</td></tr>
<tr><td>10</td><td>R12 (indicator confidence sigma) + R13 (learned drift thresholds)</td><td>Two metrology upgrades that complete the sustainability composite's honesty story and the drift detection's per-deployment tuning.</td></tr>
<tr><td>11&ndash;12</td><td>R14 (cross-language hallucination &mdash; the moat)</td><td>Starts the longest-build item while corporate-claim MVP is in production stabilisation. Per-language embeddings + claim clustering takes a full quarter to finish but the foundation lands here.</td></tr>
</table>

<p>What is <i>not</i> in this 12-week plan but stays in the long-horizon list:</p>
<ul>
  <li><b>R16 (FAIR + immutable ledger).</b> Sequence Q3 2026, once corporate claims create a population of high-stakes claims worth anchoring.</li>
  <li><b>Nature / TNFD module</b> (FAIR Tier 2 #5). October 2026 ISSB exposure draft is the trigger.</li>
  <li><b>Scope-3 supply-chain module</b> (Greenwashing &sect;5 + FAIR Tier 2 #7). After corporate-claim MVP proves out.</li>
  <li><b>Scenario engine + financial translation</b> (FAIR Tier 3 #10). Pairs with the Insurance / Risk Enterprise SKU.</li>
  <li><b>Mobile PWA</b> + WCAG 2.2 AA hardening. Quarterly cadence.</li>
  <li><b>S5 httpOnly cookies</b>, <b>D1 migration schism</b>, <b>D2 url_analyses UUID FK</b> &mdash; the three large security/data-layer chunks that should fit into a quiet week each.</li>
</ul>

<!-- ============================== 6. GITNEXUS PLAYBOOK ============================== -->
<h2>6. Gitnexus playbook &mdash; how to read this report inside the tool</h2>

<p>The 16 impact-graph blocks above are written in the same shape gitnexus expects: a primary edit, a set of fan-out files by category (schema / API / frontend / tests / ops), and an explicit risk class. When the gitnexus CLI / MCP is online, the following queries reproduce each block as a live, click-through graph.</p>

<h3>6.1 Query primitives</h3>
<pre>
# Trace from a symbol outward (e.g. who depends on bayesian_credibility.KNOWN_VENUES?)
gitnexus graph trace --from path/to/file.py:symbol --depth N

# Fan-in: who currently calls this function?
gitnexus graph fan-in --to path/to/file.py:symbol --depth N

# Emit: dump the dependency cone of a folder
gitnexus graph emit --from path/to/folder --include backend,frontend,tests

# Impact-radius: simulate edit + propagate breaks
gitnexus impact simulate --edit path/to/file.py:symbol --propagation tests,types,callers

# Diff a planned change against the current graph
gitnexus diff plan --plan docs/reports/Climatefacts-Improvement-Synthesis-2026-05-19.doc#R10
</pre>

<h3>6.2 Suggested ordered runs against this report</h3>
<table>
<tr><th>Recommendation</th><th>Gitnexus query (to verify impact radius)</th></tr>
<tr><td>R1</td><td><code>gitnexus graph fan-in --to src/backend/app/domains/intelligence/bayesian_credibility.py:KNOWN_VENUES --depth 4</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>R2</td><td><code>gitnexus graph trace --from src/backend/app/domains/intelligence/conversation_engine.py --include frontend --depth 5</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>R3</td><td><code>gitnexus graph trace --from api/methodology_routes.py:get_audit_trail --depth 3</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>R4</td><td><code>gitnexus impact simulate --edit src/backend/app/domains/intelligence/provenance.py --propagation frontend,types</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>R5</td><td><code>gitnexus graph fan-in --to src/frontend/src/components/DecomposedConfidenceChart.tsx --depth 2</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>R9</td><td><code>gitnexus graph trace --from src/backend/app/domains/intelligence/multi_llm_verifier.py:verify_claims --depth 3</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>R10</td><td><code>gitnexus graph emit --from src/backend/app/domains/content/indicators/ --pattern-as corporate</code> (use the indicator-adapter pattern as the template; emit the equivalent corporate cone)</td></tr>
<tr><td>R14</td><td><code>gitnexus impact simulate --edit src/backend/app/domains/content/embedding_service.py:DIM --propagation migrations,adapters,api,frontend</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>R16</td><td><code>gitnexus graph emit --from src/backend/services/ --pattern ledger_service</code></td></tr>
</table>

<h3>6.3 Risk-class colour mapping in the gitnexus UI</h3>
<table>
<tr><th>Class</th><th>Heuristic</th><th>UI colour</th></tr>
<tr><td>LOW</td><td>Additive; no schema; &le;5 files touched</td><td>Green</td></tr>
<tr><td>MEDIUM</td><td>Schema migration OR &gt;5 files OR feature flag required</td><td>Amber</td></tr>
<tr><td>HIGH</td><td>Re-indexes data, changes score distribution, or requires partner co-signature</td><td>Red</td></tr>
</table>

<p>The recommendations are colour-tagged in &sect;4 with the same convention (green/amber/red left border on the impact-graph table) so the report and the gitnexus UI converge.</p>

